properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow with patchy freezing rain or rain. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm. Total rainfall: 10 to 20 mm with more possible. Location: northern Nova Scotia, Annapolis Valley, and western Cape Breton Time span: continuing until late this afternoon or early evening. Remarks: A mixture of snow and rain will continue over most of mainland Nova Scotia, but snow could persist longer over higher terrain and in some parts of Cape Breton. Temperatures will hover just above zero throughout the day across the province. Rainfall warnings are in effect for the Atlantic coast while snowfall warnings are in effect for eastern parts of Cape Breton. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system is forecast to track eastwards across the southern Beaufort Sea Tuesday night into Wednesday. The Paulatuk region will experience strong southwesterly winds ahead of the system followed by strong westerly winds as it passes through. With the strong winds and a combination of a few centimetres of snow, near blizzard conditions could develop overnight Tuesday and persist through the day on Wednesday. There is still some uncertainty in the strength and track of this system, meaning that the forecast conditions described above could change as the system approaches. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system is forecast to track eastwards across the southern Beaufort Sea Tuesday night into Wednesday. The Tuktoyaktuk region can expect to see a few centimetres of snow Tuesday evening, followed immediately by strong westerly winds. Near blizzard conditions are currently forecast to develop around midnight Tuesday night, with conditions improving Wednesday morning. Meanwhile, further east, Paulatuk will experience strong southerly winds ahead of the system followed by strong northwesterly winds as it passes through. With the strong winds and a combination of a few centimetres of snow, near blizzard conditions could develop just after midnight Tuesday night and persist through the day on Wednesday. There is still some uncertainty in the strength and track of this system, meaning that the forecast conditions described above could change as the system approaches. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
